1. Imperative Commands
Concept
Imperative = You tell the cluster exactly what action to perform immediately.
You specify all parameters in the command line, and OpenShift performs the action instantly.
Think of it like:
“Create a deployment with this image and this name right now.”
Example Command
oc create deployment myapp --image=nginx
What happens
•	oc → OpenShift CLI tool
•	create deployment → command to create deployment
•	myapp → deployment name
•	--image=nginx → container image used
OpenShift immediately creates the deployment.
Other Imperative Examples
Create service
oc expose deployment myapp --port=80
Scale deployment
oc scale deployment myapp --replicas=3
Delete resource
oc delete pod podname
Advantages
✔ Quick
✔ Good for testing
✔ Easy for one-time tasks
Disadvantages
❌ Hard to track changes
❌ Not good for automation or version control
________________________________________
2. Declarative Workflow
Concept
Declarative = You describe the desired state in a file (YAML/JSON).
Instead of telling OpenShift how to do something, you describe what the final state should look like.
Example:
“There should be a deployment with 3 pods using nginx image.”
OpenShift will create or modify resources until the cluster matches the file.
________________________________________
Example YAML Manifest
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: myapp
spec:
  replicas: 3
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: myapp
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: myapp
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: nginx
        image: nginx
________________________________________
Apply Manifest
oc apply -f deployment.yaml
What it does
•	Creates deployment if not exists
•	Updates deployment if changed
________________________________________
Why Declarative is Better for Production
✔ Version control (Git)
✔ Automation (CI/CD)
✔ Reproducible infrastructure
✔ Easy updates
________________________________________
3. --save-config Option
This option saves the original configuration as an annotation in the resource.
Example:
oc create deployment myapp --image=nginx --save-config
It adds annotation like:
kubectl.kubernetes.io/last-applied-configuration
Why important?
oc apply uses this stored configuration to compare changes.
Without it, updates may behave incorrectly.
________________________________________
4. oc diff Command
Purpose
Shows difference between cluster state and manifest file before applying changes.
Example:
oc diff -f deployment.yaml
Output example:
- replicas: 2
+ replicas: 3
Meaning:
Cluster has 2 replicas, manifest wants 3 replicas.
________________________________________
Why Useful
✔ Prevents accidental changes
✔ Good for CI/CD pipelines
✔ Helps review configuration
________________________________________
5. Kustomize
Concept
Kustomize allows modifying Kubernetes/OpenShift manifests without editing the original files.
Built directly into:
oc apply
So OpenShift automatically supports Kustomize.
________________________________________
Why Kustomize is Used
Real environments usually have:
•	dev
•	test
•	staging
•	production
Instead of copying YAML files multiple times, you use:
•	base configuration
•	overlays for environments
________________________________________
6. Kustomize Structure
Typical project structure:
project/
 ├── base/
 │   ├── deployment.yaml
 │   ├── service.yaml
 │   └── kustomization.yaml
 │
 └── overlays/
     ├── dev/
     │   └── kustomization.yaml
     └── prod/
         └── kustomization.yaml
________________________________________
7. Base Directory
Base contains common configuration.
Example:
base/kustomization.yaml
resources:
- deployment.yaml
- service.yaml
Meaning:
These resources are the base application configuration.
________________________________________
8. Overlay Directory
Overlay modifies base configuration.
Example:
overlays/dev/kustomization.yaml
resources:
- ../../base

replicas:
- name: myapp
  count: 1
Example:
overlays/prod/kustomization.yaml
resources:
- ../../base

replicas:
- name: myapp
  count: 5
________________________________________
Apply overlay
Dev environment
oc apply -k overlays/dev
Production environment
oc apply -k overlays/prod
________________________________________
9. Patches in Kustomize
Sometimes you only want to change one field.
You can use patches.
Example:
patch.yaml
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: myapp
spec:
  replicas: 4
Then in kustomization.yaml:
patches:
- patch.yaml
This modifies only the replica count.
________________________________________
10. ConfigMap and Secret Generators
Kustomize can automatically generate configuration objects.
________________________________________
ConfigMap Generator
Example:
configMapGenerator:
- name: app-config
  literals:
  - ENV=dev
  - DEBUG=true
Apply:
oc apply -k .
Generated resource:
ConfigMap/app-config
________________________________________
Secret Generator
Example:
secretGenerator:
- name: db-secret
  literals:
  - password=redhat
Creates:
Secret/db-secret
________________________________________
11. oc Integration with Kustomize
You don't need a separate command.
Just run:
oc apply -k directory/
or
oc create -k directory/
OpenShift automatically processes the kustomization.yaml file.
________________________________________
Quick Comparison
Feature	Imperative	Declarative
Create resource	oc create	YAML + oc apply
Update	manual command	modify YAML
Automation	difficult	easy
Best use	testing	production
________________________________________
Real Production Workflow (Common in OpenShift)
1️⃣ Write base manifests
2️⃣ Create overlays for environments
3️⃣ Store in Git
4️⃣ Use CI/CD pipeline
5️⃣ Deploy with:
oc apply -k overlays/prod
________________________________________
